habitat: 20 feet tall, 3 inches d.b.h. Associates : Acer negundo, Carya, Fraxinus, Quercus macrocarpa, Robinia pseudoacacia, and Tilia american. Many leaves [from several trees] are morphologically odd for "pure" Quercus ellipsoidalis. Even so the moderately pubescent and slightly angular buds, glabrous red/brown twigs, and acorn cupules that are essentilally glabrous within are more suggestive of Hill's Oak with some Q. velutina influence. A neighboring tree [806.2] is Quercus x palaeolithicola [Q. ellipsoidalis x Q. velutina].
locality: Plato Township. 2.4 miles west of Randall Road on McDonald Road. Near Arlington Estates Subdivision.

habitat: 45 feet tall, 20 inches d.b.h. Associates: Carya Cordiformis, C. ovata, Juglans nigra, Quercus macrocarpa, Tilia americana, and Viburnum lantana. All acorn caps lack fringed "velutina" magrin. 2 other trees visible.
locality: Sycamore Township. Lukens Road 1.4 mile south of Base Line Road. East edge of shooting preserve.

habitat: 30 - 50 feet tall, 8 - 15 inches d.b.h. Associates: Carya, Juglans, Quercus alba, Q. macrocarpa, Q. rubra, and Ulmus. Some influence of Quercus velutina. Collected along north side of road on edge of Timber Ridge Forest Preserve. Few acorns scavenged from beneath trees. Leaves turning brown with some yellow. Acorns glabrous within from tree '.1' and look like ellipsoidalis. Pubescent within cap of tree '.2' and may be velutina. My notes indicate all of these are velutina. The undersides of leaves vary from completely glabrous to mildly hirsute in vein axils. Buds of most trees bordering old field to east are pubescent only on apical 1/2.
locality: Winfield Township. Geneva Road between Indian Knoll Road and West Branch of DuPage River.

habitat: 30 feet tall, 6 - 12 inches d.b.h. Associates: Carya ovata, Prunus serotina, Ptelea, Quercus alba, Q. macrocarpa, and Ulmus. Influence of Quercus velutina. Shore squatty buds with only terminal 1/2 hairy. Collection from two trees. This looks like Quercus ellipsoidalis from closer to home. Acorns inordinately fringed.
locality: Maryland Township. Along Adeline Road north of Coffman Road north of Adeline, Illinois.

habitat: Associates: Carya ovata, Prunus serotina, Quercus alba, Q. velutina, Robinia pseudoacacia, and Ulmus. Leaves turning crimson red. Growing within 10 feet of Quercus velutina which is still very green. South exposure. On north side of road. Yellow inner bark. Concentric rings on apex of acorns.

habitat: 30 feet tall, 8 inches d.b.h. Associates: Carya ovata, Celtis occidentalis, Quercus alba, Q. rubra, Q. velutina, and Ulmus rubra. Leaves crimson. Only acorn caps collected.
